##Gold and Silver Tan vice-president Huang Chaolin disease isolation, self-described when infected and "Drug Tester" inside

There is a process for the recognition of a disease, whether it is a specialist or a clinician

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Huang Chaolin. Photo / chinanews.com

In the early morning of January 19, the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission held a press conference to answer reporters'questions on the comprehensive prevention and control of pneumonia caused by COVID-19 in Wuhan. At that time, Huang Chaolin, an expert of the medical team of Hubei Province, deputy director and chief physician of Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, attended the press conference as an expert and answered reporters'questions. Three days later, on the 22nd, he tested positive for COVID-19 acid —— and Harvard medical school confirmed the infection.

Now, has recovered Huang Chaolin is still isolated at home, the leadership asked him to rest, but he was not idle. More than 10,000 new cases were diagnosed in Hubei Province on Feb. 13, according to an outbreak report released by the Provincial Health Commission. "from today, the number of clinically diagnosed cases in Hubei Province will be included in the number of confirmed cases, " the official explained. Huang sent the message to China News Weekly, he added: "clinically diagnosed cases = suspected cases + imaging studies. NUCLEIC ACID testing is no longer required! "

A doctor's "war sickness"

From December 29,2019 received a call from Wuhan Health Commission, Huang Chaolin's "war epidemic" has already started. As a designated hospital for medical treatment of public health emergencies in Hubei Province and Wuhan, Jinyintan Hospital is the first designated hospital for new pneumonia patients.

The 29th is Sunday, Huang Chaolin in the morning in the hospital ward turned a circle, in the afternoon to go home to rest. Home less than two hours, we received a call from Wuhan Health Commission, asked him to Hubei Province Integrated Hospital of Traditional Chinese and Western medicine to check suspicious cases.

At the time, Huang and Wu Wenjuan, director of the ICU at the hospital, donned an N95 mask and an ordinary work shirt and went to Hubei Province's integrated traditional Chinese and Western Medicine Hospital, Changjiang daily reported. Seven suspicious patients were placed in a separate area of the hospital for respiratory quarantine. Director Zhang Jixian of the Department of respiratory and critical care medicine briefed them on their admission and took them to see the patients one by one.

After some analysis and discussion, Huang Chaolin believes that these patients may be infectious, unsafe for other patients in the General Hospital, and need to be transferred to the Golden Pool Hospital, which specializes in treating infectious patients.

Huang Chaolin with a telephone to the hospital director Zhang Dingyu and Wuhan City Health Commission made a report, transferred to the negative pressure ambulance, and let the medical staff responsible for receiving wear three-level protective clothing. With the exception of one patient with mild illness who did not want to go to the Golden Pool Hospital, the transfer of the six patients lasted from late afternoon until after 11 pm.

Huang told China News weekly that he had an impression that the hospital had been receiving more and more patients with "pneumonia of unknown origin" since around January 6. Huang's epidemiological investigation of these patients began on the night of December 29.

On January 25, Huang and colleagues conducted a retrospective analysis of 41 confirmed cases of the original infection, published in the Lancet. Of the 41 cases analyzed in the paper, 14 had no history of exposure to the south China seafood market, but were still infected. In response, huang speculated that there were two reasons: "The first is that the source of exposure to the new coronavirus may not only be the south China seafood market, there may be multi-source infection; the second is that there may be human-to-human transmission, that is, patients infected from the south China Seafood Market may have infected other patients without a history of exposure to the south China seafood market through other routes. ". Although these patients are not exposed to the south China Seafood Market, they may also be infected through human-to-human transmission."

In the 25 days before his illness, in addition to seeing patients and doing scientific research, Huang Chaolin also had another important job, which was to receive multiple expert groups from the provincial, municipal and national health committees. As of January 20, there have been three groups of National Health Commission experts arrived in Han investigation.

There was no viral nucleic acid testing in the early stages of the outbreak. The first group of experts from the National Health Commission, including Li Xingwang and Cao Bin, worked with the Hubei Provincial Health Commission to develop early diagnostic criteria. At that time, the patient needed to have a history of market exposure, fever, Hypoxia, dyspnea and CT imaging to be diagnosed as new coronavirus pneumonia.

In response, Huang Chaolin said, "As far as I know, there have been five changes to the diagnostic criteria, five versions of the protocol. There is a process for the recognition of a disease, whether it is a specialist or a clinician. It should be understandable that the initial diagnostic criteria were based on the cognitive ability and level of knowledge at the time, and that the diagnostic criteria and treatment protocols were slowly being refined as the number of cases and the understanding of the condition grew."

Earlier, Zhang Dingyu, director of Jinyintan Hospital, also told China News Weekly, "In the early days of the outbreak, before the official multi-page protocol, there was a guideline for internal use. At that time, we emphasized that there was more history of epidemiology, unlike today, when there are more patients who do not have a history of exposure to the south China seafood market. At that time, experts regarded the contact history of south China seafood market as a very important basis in the epidemiological sense, and also as a diagnostic requirement and condition. This is not the opinion of a single expert, but a consensus of all, the overall expert opinion is developed by the national and provincial and municipal experts. It has something to do with the cognitive level of the event itself."

Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital. Staff Reporter / Photo by Danni Peng

In addition to receiving expert groups and conducting scientific research, as the epidemic develops, more and more patients need medical treatment, and medical personnel from other places need to be transferred and resettled. These were the duties of Huang Chaolin, then vice president of operations, who had a maximum of four hours of sleep a day. Fatigue weakened his immune system. This work state seems to be confirmed in his WECHAT: Huang Zhaolin's wechat profile picture and the cover of his friends' circle were taken in the hospital, and his signature is "down to earth, serious work. "

A patient's "war sickness. "

Huang recalled that from January 17, he felt very unwell and began to cough. At first, he mistook it for a preexisting common cold, but didn't realize it was an early sign of infection until he was diagnosed.

Recalling the cause of his infection, Huang recalled the night of January 10, when he was changing out of his protective suit and taking off his mask. As he was walking back from the clinic to his office, a patient's daughter and son-in-law recognized him and ran straight to his knees. Huang Chaolin hurried to two people up, and asked the patient's condition. In the exchange process, the husband and wife two people holding a hand of Huang Chaolin, and three people did not wear a mask. Three days later, the couple was also diagnosed with new coronary pneumonia. In Huang's mind, this was his only chance of exposure.

Huang Chaolin is 22 about 5:00 p.m. virus nucleic acid test, 9:00 p.m. out of the results, showed positive. He also had a CT scan of his lungs at around 10 p.m. , which revealed light shadows over both lungs and ground-glass lesions. After finishing the work at hand, it was 3 o'clock in the morning on the 23rd. Huang Chaolin was resting on the SOFA in his office. By this time, he was already suffering from chills and fever.

On the 23rd, Huang Chaolin took off his protective clothing and was admitted to the isolation ward of the hospital, where he changed from a doctor to a patient. At the time of admission, his sats were below 93 and he was in critical condition. On the same day, he signed his name on the clinical observation informed consent form to participate in the Kreutz test and became one of the 380"drug testers" . He had to go through his own treatment, to validate the clinical efficacy and safety of Klebsiella in the treatment of HIV in the treatment of new coronary pneumonia.

In the first 10 days after hospitalization, treatment is not smooth, "have fever, hypoxia performance, sometimes feel lung to cough out. " Huang Chaolin also appeared lung injury and breathing difficulties symptoms. Without oxygen, his sats were as low as 80 or so. There are also side effects: diarrhea, nausea, vomiting and other gastrointestinal reactions. But "it's tolerable, " Huang said

The process went on for more than a decade. In addition to Klizhi, during this period, Professor Cao Bin, vice president of china-japan Friendship Hospital, and Professor Song Jianxin of Wuhan Tongji Hospital also gave him hormone therapy, nasal tube oxygen, lung ventilation and other comprehensive treatment and support.

"Two weeks after I was diagnosed, I started getting better, " he said. It wasn't until February 4 that I stabilized. Huang Chaolin said, "I had my first nucleic acid test since February 2 and it was negative. 48 hours later, on February 4th, I had my second nucleic acid test, which was also negative, and I was discharged. He was released from the hospital and is now in isolation at home."

During the interview, the reporter heard Huang Chaolin still occasionally cough. He explained that, "It's an irritating cough. Patients who have been discharged from the hospital may experience this irritating cough or even wheezing to varying degrees, and it will take time for them to fully recover, but it will not have a significant impact on normal life,"he explained, decreased immunity is the main cause of his serious illness, but most of the patients with new pneumonia are mainly mild.

"As an expert and vice-president, I should return to work as soon as possible, " Huang said. "The current situation is quite urgent. "
